{{Jainism}}
''Acharya'' '''Dharasena''' was a ''[[Digambara monk]]'' of first century CE.

==Biography==
''Āchārya'' Dharasena, in first century CE, guided two ''Āchāryas'', ''Āchārya'' [[Pushpadanta (Jain monk)|Pushpadant]] and ''Āchārya'' [[Bhutabali]], to put the teachings of [[Mahavira]] in the written form.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jain |first=Vijay K. |title=Acharya Amritchandra's Purushartha Siddhyupaya |year=2012 |publisher=Vikalp Printers |isbn=81-903639-4-8 |url=https://books.google.co.in/books?isbn=8190363948 |quote=Non-Copyright |p=xii}}</ref> The two ''Āchāryas'' wrote, on palm leaves, ''[[Shatkhandagama|Ṣaṭkhaṅḍāgama]]''- among the oldest known ''Digambara'' Jain texts.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|pp=63–64}} Digambara tradition consider him to be the 33rd teacher in succession of [[Indrabhuti Gautama|Gautama]], 683 years after the ''[[Moksha (Jainism)|nirvana]]'' of Mahavira.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=79}}

